﻿﻿ Why not scap_check_charities: after reading scap.json, it has two gaps for this use case. (1) It only checks presence — "is any designated country mentioned?" — with no share logic, so it would flag a charity with 5% of grants going to a designated country and silently drop the policy's 25% threshold. (2) Its country check (Q3/Q5) actually happens inside an LLM prompt with the list injected — so it isn't the deterministic look-up we agreed on either; it's the same pattern, one level deeper.
▎
▎ What's implemented instead — same idea, done properly, in one compute node:
▎ 1. One LLM call, extraction only (structured output, no country list in the prompt): where the charity is established, which countries funds come from and go to, with the stated % shares. The model reads the notes; it judges nothing.
▎ 2. Plain code decides: looks each extracted country up against SENSITIVE_CHARITIES_COUNTRIES and applies the ≥25% inflow/outflow threshold. If a designated country appears but its share isn't stated, the node returns Missing Information rather than guessing.
▎ 3. It records which condition fired (established-in / inflow / outflow) — which also gives the rationale writer the exact trigger reasons from the earlier thread.
▎
▎ The "publicly known information" check stays a prompt (with the list injected) — that answer isn't in the client notes or any table, so the LLM is the only source there.
▎
▎ In short: the LLM converts prose into structured countries + shares; code makes every decision. Still open: confirming on UDP that SENSITIVE_CHARITIES_COUNTRIES matches the current "**" table (there's an unresolved TODO in scap_tree.py questioning this), and fixing Q3/Q5 in SCAPGraph itself as a follow-up since it affects the other trees.
